<subSubSection id="C63F8AFC35DAB25956953EC6C1E2537C" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="5E3439DA2E18090C2807F48CD53D105A" pageNumber="56">General discussion</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9F918FC4D461D250AAC350FE563537EC" lastPageNumber="57" pageNumber="56">
The original description of 
<taxonomicName id="FA852CBD62872429AF3EE013E8C9969B" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:152516" authority="Xu, 2000" authorityName="Xu" authorityYear="2000" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Yunodorylus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Yunodorylus sexspinus Xu" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sexspinus">Yunodorylus sexspinus</taxonomicName>
by Xu (2000) placed the newly established genus in 
<taxonomicName id="DBC9A967FDC43D830693E7AE6DC6A937" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2251" lsidName-HNS="Dorylinae Leach" pageNumber="56" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Dorylinae">Dorylinae</taxonomicName>
on account of general habitus, single segmented waist, and polymorphic worker caste. However, due to certain characters found also in 
<taxonomicName id="45DFC6ABD5E7E60C7968A6017044FD2D" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2249" lsidName-HNS="Cerapachyinae Forel" pageNumber="56" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Cerapachyinae">Cerapachyinae</taxonomicName>
, namely triangular mandibles, modified peg-like setae 
<pageStartToken id="70DC1817A04CC00783E92D2615684D35" pageNumber="57">on</pageStartToken>
pygidium, and absence of promesonotal suture, Xu concluded that the 
<taxonomicNameLabel id="3DD33DED0BB1F11543D790E4CB7D5F70" rank="genus">new genus</taxonomicNameLabel>
may represent some evolutionary link between cerapachyines and dorylines. He also provided a key to the subfamily 
<taxonomicName id="8AC603E809DAC6E645A65BB33566E9F9" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2251" lsidName-HNS="Dorylinae Leach" pageNumber="56" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Dorylinae">Dorylinae</taxonomicName>
, incorporating and differentiating 
<taxonomicName id="B437F9B20C053CEF1DB77FEB0F6002F0" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:152514" authority="Xu, 2000" authorityName="Xu" authorityYear="2000" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Yunodorylus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Yunodorylus Xu" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Yunodorylus</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="D1445A168F3F8806FAA13A290A1AE0F3" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2488" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Dorylus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Dorylus Fabricius" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Dorylus</taxonomicName>
. In 2003, Bolton synonymized 
<taxonomicName id="775D55D9957E0CF99D8A99EDD91CF10D" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:152514" authority="Xu, 2000" authorityName="Xu" authorityYear="2000" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Yunodorylus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Yunodorylus Xu" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Yunodorylus</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName id="128B1754E89A671665A2A566F189871D" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2431" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cerapachys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Cerapachys Smith" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Cerapachys</taxonomicName>
, based on the fact that the genus diagnosis provided by Xu included defining characters of 
<taxonomicName id="1F4D13BA441263AB5B9E4D76B632ADA8" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2249" lsidName-HNS="Cerapachyinae Forel" pageNumber="56" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Cerapachyinae">Cerapachyinae</taxonomicName>
but did not include any characters that could account for placement in the 
<taxonomicName id="D3077F13C2AD17756A5CA6E60DFCDA27" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2251" lsidName-HNS="Dorylinae Leach" pageNumber="56" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Dorylinae">Dorylinae</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName id="0003F7F02CE8730731891DD1A1998AC9" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:152514" authority="Xu, 2000" authorityName="Xu" authorityYear="2000" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Yunodorylus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Yunodorylus Xu" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Yunodorylus</taxonomicName>
lacks a defined promesonotal suture, large propodeal spiracle situated high and far forward, mesosomal endophragmal pit, and bidentate pygidium characteristic for 
<taxonomicName id="4210BFCB053CFB211F6798433D99129F" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2251" lsidName-HNS="Dorylinae Leach" pageNumber="56" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Dorylinae">Dorylinae</taxonomicName>
and possesses an externally visible sting, which is reduced and non-functional in 
<taxonomicName id="C0A615246F3589FEBEA2BD0E15CE194C" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2488" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Dorylus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Dorylus Fabricius" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Dorylus</taxonomicName>
. The only putative character shared by 
<taxonomicName id="13A984484E623E99653AD3C9E700931A" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:152514" authority="Xu, 2000" authorityName="Xu" authorityYear="2000" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Yunodorylus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Yunodorylus Xu" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Yunodorylus</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="17BF43D73A13FEDDB17EF31233F8368C" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2488" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Dorylus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Dorylus Fabricius" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Dorylus</taxonomicName>
and not found in cerapachyines then, would be the absence of propodeal lobes, which was stated in the original description. However, Bolton (2003) was able to examine two related species from Borneo (described here as 
<taxonomicName id="BF35F1F222F031D1822471F71AE1B460" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:251622" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cerapachys" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Cerapachys paradoxus" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paradoxus">paradoxus</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="2C7B4729C75F96B55667D19C7FF93708" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:251620" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cerapachys" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Cerapachys doryloides" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="doryloides">doryloides</taxonomicName>
), concluding that &quot; 
<taxonomicName id="A334941653C45E124347940F8A99EE94" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:152514" authority="Xu, 2000" authorityName="Xu" authorityYear="2000" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Yunodorylus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Yunodorylus Xu" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Yunodorylus</taxonomicName>
&quot; species, contrary to Xu's account, do possess propodeal lobes. Examination of 
<taxonomicName id="1CDC1EA9CB8EE9C4EAD5B553B18EAE13" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:152516" authority="Xu, 2000" authorityName="Xu" authorityYear="2000" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Yunodorylus" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Yunodorylus sexspinus Xu" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sexspinus">sexspinus</taxonomicName>
and other material in the course of this study confirms that all the species have propodeal lobes developed. Moreover, Bolton (2003) pointed out that he had already shown (Bolton 1990) morphoclinal reduction in constriction between abdominal segments III and IV among 
<taxonomicName id="8DFDB4331822D8EC2293BB9ED3CBDF62" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2431" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cerapachys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Cerapachys Smith" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Cerapachys</taxonomicName>
, leading to the condition observed in the sexspinus-group. Thus, he concluded (2003), there is nothing differentiating &quot; 
<taxonomicName id="28FC051ADA8B44E435EC93CB1A685279" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:152514" authority="Xu, 2000" authorityName="Xu" authorityYear="2000" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Yunodorylus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Yunodorylus Xu" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Yunodorylus</taxonomicName>
&quot; from 
<taxonomicName id="2B779F445D11541BF1BEAF04A0FBAD23" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2431" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cerapachys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Cerapachys Smith" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Cerapachys</taxonomicName>
as this genus is currently understood. In addition to characters discussed above, Brady &amp; Ward (2005) investigated the character of mesosomal endophragmal pit, universal in dorylines and absent in cerapachyines. These authors also recognized a thin comb of the metatibial spur as a synapomorphy of the clade of the true army ants (
<taxonomicName id="033E9C3C418F87EFE5F416952143802E" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2244" lsidName-HNS="Aenictinae Emery" pageNumber="56" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Aenictinae">Aenictinae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="D7D35804C9B36A738A3E6B021F25470D" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2245" lsidName-HNS="Aenictogitoninae Ashmead" pageNumber="56" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Aenictogitoninae">Aenictogitoninae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="C58EC59DD5FD812E32D103445203D6F2" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2251" lsidName-HNS="Dorylinae Leach" pageNumber="56" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Dorylinae">Dorylinae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="57463642F8A1A9CB0245A141485C0257" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2252" lsidName-HNS="Ecitoninae Forel" pageNumber="56" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Ecitoninae">Ecitoninae</taxonomicName>
) as opposed to the broadly pectinate comb observed in other dorylomorphs, incuding 
<taxonomicName id="0B99A85A393745BE4580707982CD7600" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2249" lsidName-HNS="Cerapachyinae Forel" pageNumber="56" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Cerapachyinae">Cerapachyinae</taxonomicName>
. Species of the sexspinus-group invariably have the metatibial spurs broadly pectinate, thus providing another character invalidating placement within 
<taxonomicName id="F2C4F3206641D9E2E6B943DE835E146A" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2251" lsidName-HNS="Dorylinae Leach" pageNumber="56" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Dorylinae">Dorylinae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B20A63F211800700E48F47ED8E2254B6" pageNumber="57">
Recently, two important phylogenies of the Formicidae derived from molecular data have been published (Moreau et al. 2006, Brady et al. 2006). Both included material of 
<taxonomicName id="79B9A26694250052FA319DF118326A04" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:183158" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cerapachys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Cerapachys sexspinus (Xu)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sexspinus">Cerapachys sexspinus</taxonomicName>
in the analysis, concluding with different results. In Moreau et al. (2006) this species appears on the tree as 
<taxonomicName id="BABDF006B7CFE4FBE59A957D21F6383F" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:152514" authority="Xu, 2000" authorityName="Xu" authorityYear="2000" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Yunodorylus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Yunodorylus Xu" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Yunodorylus</taxonomicName>
and constitutes the sister branch to 
<taxonomicName id="A8C418C7E161A170F8E9791BF9C35B66" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2433" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Sphinctomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Sphinctomyrmex Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Sphinctomyrmex</taxonomicName>
species from Australia. In analysis by Brady et al. (2006) 
<taxonomicName id="D600A92EDAAC3DD1E3C0233023CFC63E" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:183158" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cerapachys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Cerapachys sexspinus (Xu)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sexspinus">Cerapachys sexspinus</taxonomicName>
appears sister to the clade of 
<taxonomicName id="75703F2E97E8BE3EE1C3D00D6477BD7F" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2244" lsidName-HNS="Aenictinae Emery" pageNumber="57" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Aenictinae">Aenictinae</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName id="10C90AB99609FA1CBB22E24229D93476" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2252" lsidName-HNS="Ecitoninae Forel" pageNumber="57" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Ecitoninae">Ecitoninae</taxonomicName>
. However, in both studies these nodes were relatively weakly supported. On account of this fact and the strong morphological evidence discussed above, it seems highly improbable that this group is more closely related to the true army ants than to other cerapachyines. However, it is worth bearing in mind that the internal phylogeny of the 
<taxonomicName id="BEEDD304AEE30F4F443D8E13D1C7D012" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2249" lsidName-HNS="Cerapachyinae Forel" pageNumber="57" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Cerapachyinae">Cerapachyinae</taxonomicName>
is unresolved and recent studies suggest paraphyly of this subfamily (Brady &amp; Ward 2005, Moreau et al. 2006, Brady et al. 2006).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="27F4157E801F56644959A13189051575" pageNumber="57">
Species in the Cerapachys sexspinus-group possess a unique character combination that could easily account for placement in a genus of their own, as compared with generic concepts in other ant groups. Although these species are very distinctive within 
<taxonomicName id="E3CD137FC20DFCB6136ADB9EC0E288E4" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2431" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cerapachys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Cerapachys Smith" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Cerapachys</taxonomicName>
, most notably by having a single segmented waist and unique spur formula, it seems premature to resurrect the genus name 
<taxonomicName id="0076E3A42B42A982F2F38EC57821C240" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:152514" authority="Xu, 2000" authorityName="Xu" authorityYear="2000" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Yunodorylus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Yunodorylus Xu" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Yunodorylus</taxonomicName>
. The genus 
<taxonomicName id="BCBDDBE8BE0ED2ED7DF277CDD43CBBE2" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2431" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cerapachys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Cerapachys Smith" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Cerapachys</taxonomicName>
, as presently understood, encompasses an enormous diversity of morphological traits (Brown 1975, Bolton 1990, Bolton 2003). For example, species related to 
<taxonomicName id="C49FE9689CC2A8096DEC0A19C7F1E0F9" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:27889" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cerapachys" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Cerapachys crawleyi Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crawleyi">C. crawleyi Wheeler</taxonomicName>
, 1924 have quite exceptional morphology and at times have been placed in a genus of their own, Chrysapace Crawley, 1924. They also possess unique palp (5,3) and spur (2p,2p) formulas, and on this ground would deserve reviving their generic status. Therefore, until broader revision of genera and their status in the subfamily is attempted, rank change of the species-group discussed above would be an act of inconsequence. Full generic revision of the subfamily is beyond the scope of this study, and it is recommended that any changes at the generic level should be postponed until the internal phylogeny of the 
<taxonomicName id="7C3BAAE6C1D1B4BF4B039EFBC42FA04F" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2249" lsidName-HNS="Cerapachyinae Forel" pageNumber="57" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Cerapachyinae">Cerapachyinae</taxonomicName>
is better understood.
</paragraph>
